            <div id="hungerford-algebra" style="background: #ffffff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; padding: 2rem; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0,0,0,0.05); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                <h2 style="color: #3b82f6; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Chapter 1: Groups</h2>
                
                <p style="color: #334155; line-height: 1.8;">
                    A group is a nonempty set $G$ together with a binary operation on $G$ (denoted by juxtaposition) such that the following axioms are satisfied:
                </p>
                
                <ul style="color: #334155; line-height: 1.8;">
                    <li><strong>Associativity:</strong> For all $a, b, c \in G$, $(ab)c = a(bc)$.</li>
                    <li><strong>Identity:</strong> There exists an element $e \in G$ such that for all $a \in G$, $ea = ae = a$.</li>
                    <li><strong>Inverse:</strong> For each $a \in G$, there exists an element $a^{-1} \in G$ such that $aa^{-1} = a^{-1}a = e$.</li>
                </ul>

                <p style="color: #334155; line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 1.5rem;">
                    Consider a homomorphism of groups $\varphi: G \to H$. The relationship between the kernel and the image is given by the First Isomorphism Theorem:
                </p>

                <div style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; color: #0f172a;">
                    $$ G / \ker(\varphi) \cong \text{Im}(\varphi) $$
                </div>

                <p style="color: #334155; line-height: 1.8;">
                    This fundamental theorem establishes that the quotient of the domain by the kernel is isomorphic to the image of the homomorphism.
                </p>
            </div>

